# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: homomorphic-encryption
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Digital data can be contrasted with *analog data*, which is represented by a value from a continuous range of real numbers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Analog data is transmitted by an analog signal, which not only takes on continuous values but can vary continuously with time, a continuous real-valued function of time.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] An example is the air pressure variation in a sound wave.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data requires interpretation to become information.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In modern (post-1960) computer systems, all data is digital.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The word *digital* comes from the same source as the words digit and *digitus* (the Latin word for *finger*), as fingers are often used for counting.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Mathematician George Stibitz of Bell Telephone Laboratories used the word *digital* in reference to the fast electric pulses emitted by a device designed to aim and fire anti-aircraft guns in 1942.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The term is most commonly used in computing and electronics, especially where real-world information is converted to binary numeric form as in digital audio and digital photography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Since symbols (for example, alphanumeric characters) are not continuous, representing symbols digitally is rather simpler than conversion of continuous or analog information to digital.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Instead of sampling and quantization as in analog-to-digital conversion, such techniques as polling and encoding are used.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A symbol input device usually consists of a group of switches that are polled at regular intervals to see which switches are switched.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data will be lost if, within a single polling interval, two switches are pressed, or a switch is pressed, released, and pressed again.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This polling can be done by a specialized processor in the device to prevent burdening the main CPU.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] When a new symbol has been entered, the device typically sends an interrupt, in a specialized format, so that the CPU can read it.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] For devices with only a few switches (such as the buttons on a joystick), the status of each can be encoded as bits (usually 0 for released and 1 for pressed) in a single word.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This is useful when combinations of key presses are meaningful, and is sometimes used for passing the status of modifier keys on a keyboard (such as shift and control).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] But it does not scale to support more keys than the number of bits in a single byte or word.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Devices with many switches (such as a computer keyboard) usually arrange these switches in a scan matrix, with the individual switches on the intersections of x and y lines.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] When a switch is pressed, it connects the corresponding x and y lines together.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Polling (often called scanning in this case) is done by activating each x line in sequence and detecting which y lines then have a signal, thus which keys are pressed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] When the keyboard processor detects that a key has changed state, it sends a signal to the CPU indicating the scan code of the key and its new state.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The symbol is then encoded or converted into a number based on the status of modifier keys and the desired character encoding.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A custom encoding can be used for a specific application with no loss of data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] However, using a standard encoding such as ASCII is problematic if a symbol such as 'ß' needs to be converted but is not in the standard.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] It is estimated that in the year 1986, less than 1% of the world's technological capacity to store information was digital and in 2007 it was already 94%.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The year 2002 is assumed to be the year when humankind was able to store more information in digital than in analog format (the "beginning of the digital age").
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Digital data come in these three states: data at rest, data in transit, and data in use.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The confidentiality, integrity, and availability have to be managed during the entire lifecycle from 'birth' to the destruction of the data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] While it is generally accepted that archive data (i.e. which never changes), regardless of its storage medium, is data at rest and active data subject to constant or frequent change is data in use. “Inactive data” could be taken to mean data which may change, but infrequently.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The imprecise nature of terms such as “constant” and “frequent” means that some stored data cannot be comprehensively defined as either data at rest or in use.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] These definitions could be taken to assume that Data at Rest is a superset of data in use; however, data in use, subject to frequent change, has distinct processing requirements from data at rest, whether completely static or subject to occasional change.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Because of its nature data at rest is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect data in motion and increasingly promoted for protecting data at rest.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The encryption of data at rest should only include strong encryption methods such as AES or RSA.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Encrypted data should remain encrypted when access controls such as usernames and password fail.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Increasing encryption on multiple levels is recommended.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Cryptography can be implemented on the database housing the data and on the physical storage where the databases are stored.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data encryption keys should be updated on a regular basis.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Encryption keys should be stored separately from the data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Encryption also enables crypto-shredding at the end of the data or hardware lifecycle.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Periodic auditing of sensitive data should be part of policy and should occur on scheduled occurrences.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Finally, only store the minimum possible amount of sensitive data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens, which have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This process does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Tokens require significantly less computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This is achieved by keeping specific data fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Lower processing and storage requirements makes tokenization an ideal method of securing data at rest in systems that manage large volumes of data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A further method of preventing unwanted access to data at rest is the use of data federation especially when data is distributed globally (e.g. in off-shore archives).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] An example of this would be a European organisation which stores its archived data off-site in the US.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Under the terms of the USA PATRIOT Act the American authorities can demand access to all data physically stored within its boundaries, even if it includes personal information on European citizens with no connections to the US.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data encryption alone cannot be used to prevent this as the authorities have the right to demand decrypted information.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A data federation policy which retains personal citizen information with no foreign connections within its country of origin (separate from information which is either not personal or is relevant to off-shore authorities) is one option to address this concern.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] However, data stored in foreign countries can be accessed using legislation in the CLOUD Act.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Some cloud software as a service (SaaS) providers refer to data in use as any data currently being processed by applications, as the CPU and memory are utilized.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Because of its nature, data in use is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data in use, or memory, can contain sensitive data including digital certificates, encryption keys, intellectual property (software algorithms, design data), and personally identifiable information.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Compromising data in use enables access to encrypted data at rest and data in motion.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] For example, someone with access to random access memory can parse that memory to locate the encryption key for data at rest.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Once they have obtained that encryption key, they can decrypt encrypted data at rest.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Threats to data in use can come in the form of cold boot attacks, malicious hardware devices, rootkits and bootkits.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect Data in Motion and Data at Rest and increasingly recognized as an optimal method for protecting Data in Use.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] There have been multiple projects to encrypt memory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Microsoft Xbox systems are designed to provide memory encryption and the company PrivateCore presently has a commercial software product vCage to provide attestation along with full memory encryption for x86 servers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Several papers have been published highlighting the availability of security-enhanced x86 and ARM commodity processors.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In that work, an ARM Cortex-A8 processor is used as the substrate on which a full memory encryption solution is built.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Process segments (for example, stack, code or heap) can be encrypted individually or in composition.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This work marks the first full memory encryption implementation on a mobile general-purpose commodity processor.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The system provides both confidentiality and integrity protections of code and data which are encrypted everywhere outside the CPU boundary.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] For x86 systems, AMD has a Secure Memory Encryption (SME) feature introduced in 2017 with Epyc.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Intel has promised to deliver its Total Memory Encryption (TME) feature in an upcoming CPU.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Operating system kernel patches such as TRESOR and Loop-Amnesia modify the operating system so that CPU registers can be used to store encryption keys and avoid holding encryption keys in RAM.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] While this approach is not general purpose and does not protect all data in use, it does protect against cold boot attacks.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Encryption keys are held inside the CPU rather than in RAM so that data at rest encryption keys are protected against attacks that might compromise encryption keys in memory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Enclaves enable an “enclave” to be secured with encryption in RAM so that enclave data is encrypted while in RAM but available as clear text inside the CPU and CPU cache.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Intel Corporation has introduced the concept of “enclaves” as part of its Software Guard Extensions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Intel revealed an architecture combining software and CPU hardware in technical papers published in 2013.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Several cryptographic tools, including secure multi-party computation and homomorphic encryption, allow for the private computation of data on untrusted systems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data in use could be operated upon while encrypted and never exposed to the system doing the processing.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data in transit can be separated into two categories: information that flows over the public or untrusted network such as the Internet and data that flows in the confines of a private network such as a corporate or enterprise local area network (LAN).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data within a computer, in most cases, moves as parallel data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data moving to or from a computer, in most cases, moves as serial data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data sourced from an analog device, such as a temperature sensor, may be converted to digital using an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data representing quantities, characters, or symbols on which operations are performed by a computer are stored and recorded on magnetic, optical, electronic, or mechanical recording media, and transmitted in the form of digital electrical or optical signals.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data pass in and out of computers via peripheral devices.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Physical computer memory elements consist of an address and a byte/word of data storage.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Digital data are often stored in relational databases, like tables or SQL databases, and can generally be represented as abstract key/value pairs.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data can be organized in many different types of data structures, including arrays, graphs, and objects.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data structures can store data of many different types, including numbers, strings and even other data structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Metadata helps translate data to information.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Metadata may be implied, specified or given.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data relating to physical events or processes will have a temporal component.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This is the case when a device such as a temperature logger receives data from a temperature sensor.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] When the temperature is received it is assumed that the data has a temporal reference of *now*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] So the device records the date, time and temperature together.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] When the data logger communicates temperatures, it must also report the date and time as metadata for each temperature reading.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Fundamentally, computers follow a sequence of instructions they are given in the form of data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A set of instructions to perform a given task (or tasks) is called a *program*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A program is data in the form of coded instructions to control the operation of a computer or other machine.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In the nominal case, the program, as executed by the computer, will consist of machine code.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The elements of storage manipulated by the program, but not actually executed by the central processing unit (CPU), are also data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] At its most essential, a single datum is a value stored at a specific location.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Therefore, it is possible for computer programs to operate on other computer programs, by manipulating their programmatic data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] To store data bytes in a file, they have to be serialized in a file format.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Typically, programs are stored in special file types, different from those used for other data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Executable files contain programs; all other files are also data files.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] However, executable files may also contain data used by the program which is built into the program.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In particular, some executable files have a data segment, which nominally contains constants and initial values for variables, both of which can be considered data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The line between program and data can become blurry.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] An interpreter, for example, is a program.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The input data to an interpreter is itself a program, just not one expressed in native machine language.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In many cases, the interpreted program will be a human-readable text file, which is manipulated with a text editor program.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Metaprogramming similarly involves programs manipulating other programs as data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Programs like compilers, linkers, debuggers, program updaters, virus scanners and such use other programs as their data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] For example, a user might first instruct the operating system to load a word processor program from one file, and then use the running program to open and edit a document stored in another file.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In this example, the document would be considered data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] If the word processor also features a spell checker, then the dictionary (word list) for the spell checker would also be considered data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The algorithms used by the spell checker to suggest corrections would be either machine code data or text in some interpretable programming language.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In an alternate usage, binary files (which are not human-readable) are sometimes called *data* as distinguished from human-readable *text*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The total amount of digital data in 2007 was estimated to be 281 billion gigabytes (281 exabytes).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Keys in data provide the context for values.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Regardless of the structure of data, there is always a key component present.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Keys in data and data-structures are essential for giving meaning to data values.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Without a key that is directly or indirectly associated with a value, or collection of values in a structure, the values become meaningless and cease to be data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] That is to say, there has to be a key component linked to a value component in order for it to be considered data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Random access memory (RAM) holds data that the CPU has direct access to.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] A CPU may only manipulate data within its processor registers or memory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This is as opposed to data storage, where the CPU must direct the transfer of data between the storage device (disk, tape...) and memory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] RAM is an array of linear contiguous locations that a processor may read or write by providing an address for the read or write operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The processor may operate on any location in memory at any time in any order.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In RAM the smallest element of data is the binary bit.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The capabilities and limitations of accessing RAM are processor specific.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In general main memory is arranged as an array of locations beginning at address 0 (hexadecimal 0).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Each location can store usually 8 or 32 bits depending on the computer architecture.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data keys need not be a direct hardware address in memory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Indirect, abstract and logical keys codes can be stored in association with values to form a data structure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data structures have predetermined offsets (or links or paths) from the start of the structure, in which data values are stored.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Therefore, the data key consists of the key to the structure plus the offset (or links or paths) into the structure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In such an organization of data, the data key is usually a value in one (or a composite of the values in several) of the columns.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The tabular view of repeating data structures is only one of many possibilities.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Repeating data structures can be organised hierarchically, such that nodes are linked to each other in a cascade of parent-child relationships.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Values and potentially more complex data-structures are linked to the nodes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Thus the nodal hierarchy provides the key for addressing the data structures associated with the nodes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This representation can be thought of as an inverted tree.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Modern computer operating system file systems are a common example; and XML is another.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Data has some inherent features when it is sorted on a key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] All the values for subsets of the key appear together.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] When passing sequentially through groups of the data with the same key, or a subset of the key changes, this is referred to in data processing circles as a break, or a control break.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] It particularly facilitates the aggregation of data values on subsets of a key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Until the advent of bulk non-volatile memory like flash, persistent data storage was traditionally achieved by writing the data to external block devices like magnetic tape and disk drives.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] These devices typically seek to a location on the magnetic media and then read or write blocks of data of a predetermined size.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In this case, the seek location on the media, is the data key and the blocks are the data values.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Early used *raw disk* data file-systems or disc operating systems reserved contiguous blocks on the disc drive for data files.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In those systems, the files could be filled up, running out of data space before all the data had been written to them.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Thus much unused data space was reserved unproductively to ensure adequate free space for each file.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Later file-systems introduced partitions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] They reserved blocks of disc data space for partitions and used the allocated blocks more economically, by dynamically assigning blocks of a partition to a file as needed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] To achieve this, the file system had to keep track of which blocks were used or unused by data files in a catalog or file allocation table.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Though this made better use of the disc data space, it resulted in fragmentation of files across the disc, and a concomitant performance overhead due additional seek time to read the data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Modern file systems reorganize fragmented files dynamically to optimize file access times.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Further developments in file systems resulted in virtualization of disc drives i.e. where a logical drive can be defined as partitions from a number of physical drives.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Retrieving a small subset of data from a much larger set may imply inefficiently searching through the data sequentially.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] **Indexes** are a way to copy out keys and location addresses from data structures in files, tables and data sets, then organize them using inverted tree structures to reduce the time taken to retrieve a subset of the original data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In order to do this, the key of the subset of data to be retrieved must be known before retrieval begins.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The most popular indexes are the B-tree and the dynamic hash key indexing methods.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Indexing is overhead for filing and retrieving data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] There are other ways of organizing indexes, e.g. sorting the keys and using a binary search algorithm.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] 2. at run time, the creation of references to in-memory data-structures of objects that have been instantiated from a class library.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] It is only after instantiation that an object of a specified class exists.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] After an object's reference is cleared, the object also ceases to exist.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The memory locations where the object's data was stored are garbage and are reclassified as unused memory available for reuse.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] The advent of databases introduced a further layer of abstraction for persistent data storage.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Databases use metadata, and a structured query language protocol between client and server systems, communicating over a computer network, using a two phase commit logging system to ensure transactional completeness, when saving data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Modern scalable and high-performance data persistence technologies, such as Apache Hadoop, rely on massively parallel distributed data processing across many commodity computers on a high bandwidth network.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] In such systems, the data is distributed across multiple computers and therefore any particular computer in the system must be represented in the key of the data, either directly, or indirectly.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] This enables the differentiation between two identical sets of data, each being processed on a different computer at the same time.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/data-in-use] Even though digital signals are generally associated with the binary electronic digital systems used in modern electronics and computing, digital systems are actually ancient, and need not be binary or electronic.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] As an example of a practical application of homomorphic encryption: encrypted photographs can be scanned for points of interest, without revealing the contents of a photo.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] However, observation of side-channels can see a photograph being sent to a point-of-interest lookup service, revealing the fact that photographs were taken.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Thus, homomorphic encryption eliminates the need for processing data in the clear, thereby preventing attacks that would enable an attacker to access that data while it is being processed, using privilege escalation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] For sensitive data, such as healthcare information, homomorphic encryption can be used to enable new services by removing privacy barriers inhibiting data sharing or increasing security to existing services.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] For example, predictive analytics in healthcare can be hard to apply via a third-party service provider due to medical data privacy concerns.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] But if the predictive-analytics service provider could operate on encrypted data instead, without having the decryption keys, these privacy concerns are diminished.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Moreover, even if the service provider's system is compromised, the data would remain secure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption is a form of encryption with an additional evaluation capability for computing over encrypted data without access to the secret key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The result of such a computation remains encrypted.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption can be viewed as an extension of public-key cryptography, because ciphertexts can be manipulated algebraically to produce an encrypted result corresponding to operations on the underlying plaintexts.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] *Homomorphic* refers to homomorphism in algebra: the encryption and decryption functions can be thought of as homomorphisms between plaintext and ciphertext spaces.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption includes multiple types of encryption schemes that can perform different classes of computations over encrypted data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The computations are represented as either Boolean or arithmetic circuits.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] For the majority of homomorphic encryption schemes, the multiplicative depth of circuits is the main practical limitation in performing computations over encrypted data.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes are inherently malleable.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] In terms of malleability, homomorphic encryption schemes have weaker security properties than non-homomorphic schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] A cryptosystem that supports *arbitrary computation* on ciphertexts is known as fully homomorphic encryption (FHE).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Such a scheme enables the construction of programs for any desirable functionality, which can be run on encrypted inputs to produce an encryption of the result.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Since such a program need never decrypt its inputs, it can be run by an untrusted party without revealing its inputs and internal state.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Fully homomorphic cryptosystems have great practical implications in the outsourcing of private computations, for instance, in the context of cloud computing.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes have been developed using different approaches.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Specifically, fully homomorphic encryption schemes are often grouped into generations corresponding to the underlying approach.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The problem of constructing a fully homomorphic encryption scheme was first proposed in 1978, within a year of publishing of the RSA scheme.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] For more than 30 years, it was unclear whether a solution existed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Craig Gentry, using lattice-based cryptography, described the first plausible construction for a fully homomorphic encryption scheme in 2009.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's scheme supports both addition and multiplication operations on ciphertexts, from which it is possible to construct circuits for performing arbitrary computation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Gentry then shows how to slightly modify this scheme to make it *bootstrappable*, i.e., capable of evaluating its own decryption circuit and then at least one more operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Finally, he shows that any bootstrappable somewhat homomorphic encryption scheme can be converted into a fully homomorphic encryption through a recursive self-embedding.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] For Gentry's "noisy" scheme, the bootstrapping procedure effectively "refreshes" the ciphertext by applying to it the decryption procedure homomorphically, thereby obtaining a new ciphertext that encrypts the same value as before but has lower noise.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] By "refreshing" the ciphertext periodically whenever the noise grows too large, it is possible to compute an arbitrary number of additions and multiplications without increasing the noise too much.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Gentry based the security of his scheme on the assumed hardness of two problems: certain worst-case problems over ideal lattices, and the sparse (or low-weight) subset sum problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's Ph.D. thesis provides additional details.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The Gentry-Halevi implementation of Gentry's original cryptosystem reported a timing of about 30 minutes per basic bit operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Extensive design and implementation work in subsequent years have improved upon these early implementations by many orders of magnitude runtime performance.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] In 2010, Marten van Dijk, Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi and Vinod Vaikuntanathan presented a second fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which uses many of the tools of Gentry's construction, but which does not require ideal lattices.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Instead, they show that the somewhat homomorphic component of Gentry's ideal lattice-based scheme can be replaced with a very simple somewhat homomorphic scheme that uses integers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The scheme is therefore conceptually simpler than Gentry's ideal lattice scheme, but has similar properties with regards to homomorphic operations and efficiency.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The somewhat homomorphic component in the work of Van Dijk et al. is similar to an encryption scheme proposed by Levieil and Naccache in 2008, and also to one that was proposed by Bram Cohen in 1998.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Cohen's method is not even additively homomorphic, however.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The Levieil–Naccache scheme supports only additions, but it can be modified to also support a small number of multiplications.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Many refinements and optimizations of the scheme of Van Dijk et al. were proposed in a sequence of works by Jean-Sébastien Coron, Tancrède Lepoint, Avradip Mandal, David Naccache, and Mehdi Tibouchi.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Some of these works included also implementations of the resulting schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The homomorphic cryptosystems of this generation are derived from techniques that were developed starting in 2011–2012 by Zvika Brakerski, Craig Gentry, Vinod Vaikuntanathan, and others.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] These innovations led to the development of much more efficient somewhat and fully homomorphic cryptosystems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The security of most of these schemes is based on the hardness of the (Ring) Learning With Errors (RLWE) problem, except for the LTV and BLLN schemes that rely on an *overstretched* variant of the NTRU computational problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] This NTRU variant was subsequently shown vulnerable to subfield lattice attacks, which is why these two schemes are no longer used in practice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] All the second-generation cryptosystems still follow the basic blueprint of Gentry's original construction, namely they first construct a somewhat homomorphic cryptosystem and then convert it to a fully homomorphic cryptosystem using bootstrapping.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] A distinguishing characteristic of the second-generation cryptosystems is that they all feature a much slower growth of the noise during the homomorphic computations.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Additional optimizations by Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi, and Nigel Smart resulted in cryptosystems with nearly optimal asymptotic complexity: Performing T operations on data encrypted with security parameter k has complexity of only $T\cdot \mathrm {polylog} (k)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] These optimizations build on the Smart-Vercauteren techniques that enable packing of many plaintext values in a single ciphertext and operating on all these plaintext values in a SIMD fashion.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Many of the advances in these second-generation cryptosystems were also ported to the cryptosystem over the integers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Another distinguishing feature of second-generation schemes is that they are efficient enough for many applications even without invoking bootstrapping, instead operating in the leveled FHE mode.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] In 2013, Craig Gentry, Amit Sahai, and Brent Waters (GSW) proposed a new technique for building FHE schemes that avoids an expensive "relinearization" step in homomorphic multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Zvika Brakerski and Vinod Vaikuntanathan observed that for certain types of circuits, the GSW cryptosystem features an even slower growth rate of noise, and hence better efficiency and stronger security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Jacob Alperin-Sheriff and Chris Peikert then described a very efficient bootstrapping technique based on this observation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] These techniques were further improved to develop efficient ring variants of the GSW cryptosystem: FHEW (2014) and TFHE (2016).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The FHEW scheme was the first to show that by refreshing the ciphertexts after every single operation, it is possible to reduce the bootstrapping time to a fraction of a second.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] FHEW introduced a new method to compute Boolean gates on encrypted data that greatly simplifies bootstrapping and implemented a variant of the bootstrapping procedure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The efficiency of FHEW was further improved by the TFHE scheme, which implements a ring variant of the bootstrapping procedure using a method similar to the one in FHEW.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] In 2016, Jung Hee Cheon, Andrey Kim, Miran Kim, and Yongsoo Song (CKKS) proposed an approximate homomorphic encryption scheme that supports a special kind of fixed-point arithmetic that is commonly referred to as block floating point arithmetic.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The CKKS scheme includes an efficient rescaling operation that scales down an encrypted message after a multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] For comparison, such rescaling requires bootstrapping in the BGV and BFV schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The rescaling operation makes CKKS scheme the most efficient method for evaluating polynomial approximations, and is the preferred approach for implementing privacy-preserving machine learning applications.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The scheme introduces several approximation errors, both nondeterministic and deterministic, that require special handling in practice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] A 2020 article by Baiyu Li and Daniele Micciancio discusses passive attacks against CKKS, suggesting that the standard IND-CPA definition may not be sufficient in scenarios where decryption results are shared.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The authors apply the attack to four modern homomorphic encryption libraries (HEAAN, SEAL, HElib and PALISADE) and report that it is possible to recover the secret key from decryption results in several parameter configurations.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The authors also propose mitigation strategies for these attacks, and include a Responsible Disclosure in the paper suggesting that the homomorphic encryption libraries already implemented mitigations for the attacks before the article became publicly available.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Further information on the mitigation strategies implemented in the homomorphic encryption libraries has also been published.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] In the following examples, the notation ${\mathcal {E}}(x)$ is used to denote the encryption of the message x .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] where $\oplus$ denotes addition modulo 2, (i.e., exclusive-or).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] There are several open-source implementations of partially, somewhat and fully homomorphic encryption schemes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Second-generation and fourth-generation FHE scheme implementations typically operate in the leveled FHE mode (though bootstrapping is still available in some libraries) and support efficient SIMD-like packing of data; they are typically used to compute on encrypted integers or real/complex numbers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Third-generation FHE scheme implementations often bootstrap after each operation but have limited support for packing; they were initially used to compute Boolean circuits over encrypted bits, but have been extended to support integer arithmetics and univariate function evaluation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] The choice of using a second-generation vs. third-generation vs fourth-generation scheme depends on the input data types and the desired computation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] General-purpose lattice cryptography library.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] TFHE-extended compiler with a Python Frontend.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] Verifiable encrypted computations based on Rinocchio ZKP and BGV homomorphic Encryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/fully-homomorphic-encryption] In 2017, researchers from IBM, Microsoft, Intel, the NIST, and others formed the open Homomorphic Encryption Standardization Consortium, which maintains a community security Homomorphic Encryption Standard.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In algebra, a **homomorphism** is a structure-preserving map between two algebraic structures of the same type (such as two groups, two rings, or two vector spaces).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The word *homomorphism* comes from the Ancient Greek language: ὁμός (*homos*) meaning "same" and μορφή (*morphe*) meaning "form" or "shape".
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] However, the word was apparently introduced to mathematics due to a (mis)translation of German *ähnlich* meaning "similar" to ὁμός meaning "same".
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The term "homomorphism" appeared as early as 1892, when it was attributed to the German mathematician Felix Klein (1849–1925).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Homomorphisms of vector spaces are also called linear maps, and their study is the subject of linear algebra.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The concept of homomorphism has been generalized, under the name of morphism, to many other structures that either do not have an underlying set, or are not algebraic.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] This generalization is the starting point of category theory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A homomorphism may also be an isomorphism, an endomorphism, an automorphism, etc.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Each of those can be defined in a way that may be generalized to any class of morphisms.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A homomorphism is a map between two algebraic structures of the same type (e.g. two groups, two fields, two vector spaces), that preserves the operations of the structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] One says often that f preserves the operation or is compatible with the operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The operations that must be preserved by a homomorphism include 0-ary operations, that is the constants.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In particular, when an identity element is required by the type of structure, the identity element of the first structure must be mapped to the corresponding identity element of the second structure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] An algebraic structure may have more than one operation, and a homomorphism is required to preserve each operation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Thus a map that preserves only some of the operations is not a homomorphism of the structure, but only a homomorphism of the substructure obtained by considering only the preserved operations.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For example, a map between monoids that preserves the monoid operation and not the identity element, is not a monoid homomorphism, but only a semigroup homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The notation for the operations does not need to be the same in the source and the target of a homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For example, the real numbers form a group for addition, and the positive real numbers form a group for multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] and is thus a homomorphism between these two groups.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] $\ln(xy)=\ln(x)+\ln(y),$ and is also a group homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The real numbers are a ring, having both addition and multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The set of all 2×2 matrices is also a ring, under matrix addition and matrix multiplication.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For another example, the nonzero complex numbers form a group under the operation of multiplication, as do the nonzero real numbers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] That is, f is the absolute value (or modulus) of the complex number z .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] As another example, the diagram shows a monoid homomorphism f from the monoid $(\mathbb {N} ,+,0)$ to the monoid $(\mathbb {N} ,\times ,1)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Due to the different names of corresponding operations, the structure preservation properties satisfied by f amount to $f(x+y)=f(x)\times f(y)$ and $f(0)=1$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A composition algebra A over a field F has a quadratic form, called a *norm*, $N:A\to F$ , which is a group homomorphism from the multiplicative group of A to the multiplicative group of F .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Several kinds of homomorphisms have a specific name, which is also defined for general morphisms.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] An isomorphism between algebraic structures of the same type is commonly defined as a bijective homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In the more general context of category theory, an isomorphism is defined as a morphism that has an inverse that is also a morphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In the specific case of algebraic structures, the two definitions are equivalent, although they may differ for non-algebraic structures, which have an underlying set.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] If A and B have underlying sets, and $f:A\to B$ has an inverse g , then f is bijective.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In fact, f is injective, as $f(x)=f(y)$ implies $x=g(f(x))=g(f(y))=y$ , and f is surjective, as, for any x in B , one has $x=f(g(x))$ , and x is the image of an element of A .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Conversely, if $f:A\to B$ is a bijective homomorphism between algebraic structures, let $g:B\to A$ be the map such that $g(y)$ is the unique element x of A such that $f(x)=y$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] One has $f\circ g=\operatorname {Id} _{B}{\text{ and }}g\circ f=\operatorname {Id} _{A},$ and it remains only to show that *g* is a homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] and g is thus compatible with $*.$ As the proof is similar for any arity, this shows that g is a homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] This proof does not work for non-algebraic structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For example, for topological spaces, a morphism is a continuous map, and the inverse of a bijective continuous map is not necessarily continuous.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] An isomorphism of topological spaces, called homeomorphism or bicontinuous map, is thus a bijective continuous map, whose inverse is also continuous.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] An endomorphism is a homomorphism whose domain equals the codomain, or, more generally, a morphism whose source is equal to its target.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The endomorphisms of an algebraic structure, or of an object of a category, form a monoid under composition.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The endomorphisms of a vector space or of a module form a ring.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In the case of a vector space or a free module of finite dimension, the choice of a basis induces a ring isomorphism between the ring of endomorphisms and the ring of square matrices of the same dimension.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] An automorphism is an endomorphism that is also an isomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The automorphisms of an algebraic structure or of an object of a category form a group under composition, which is called the automorphism group of the structure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Many groups that have received a name are automorphism groups of some algebraic structure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For example, the general linear group $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(k)$ is the automorphism group of a vector space of dimension n over a field k .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The automorphism groups of fields were introduced by Évariste Galois for studying the roots of polynomials, and are the basis of Galois theory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For algebraic structures, monomorphisms are commonly defined as injective homomorphisms.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In the more general context of category theory, a monomorphism is defined as a morphism that is **left cancelable**.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] This means that a (homo)morphism $f:A\to B$ is a monomorphism if, for any pair g , h of morphisms from any other object C to A , then $f\circ g=f\circ h$ implies $g=h$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] These two definitions of *monomorphism* are equivalent for all common algebraic structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In particular, the two definitions of a monomorphism are equivalent for sets, magmas, semigroups, monoids, groups, rings, fields, vector spaces and modules.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A **split monomorphism** is a homomorphism that has a left inverse and thus it is itself a right inverse of that other homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] That is, a homomorphism $f\colon A\to B$ is a split monomorphism if there exists a homomorphism $g\colon B\to A$ such that $g\circ f=\operatorname {Id} _{A}.$ A split monomorphism is always a monomorphism, for both meanings of *monomorphism*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For sets and vector spaces, every monomorphism is a split monomorphism, but this property does not hold for most common algebraic structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In algebra, **epimorphisms** are often defined as surjective homomorphisms.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] On the other hand, in category theory, epimorphisms are defined as **right cancelable** morphisms.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] This means that a (homo)morphism $f:A\to B$ is an epimorphism if, for any pair g , h of morphisms from B to any other object C , the equality $g\circ f=h\circ f$ implies $g=h$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A surjective homomorphism is always right cancelable, but the converse is not always true for algebraic structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] However, the two definitions of *epimorphism* are equivalent for sets, vector spaces, abelian groups, modules (see below for a proof), and groups.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The importance of these structures in all mathematics, especially in linear algebra and homological algebra, may explain the coexistence of two non-equivalent definitions.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Algebraic structures for which there exist non-surjective epimorphisms include semigroups and rings.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The most basic example is the inclusion of integers into rational numbers, which is a homomorphism of rings and of multiplicative semigroups.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For both structures it is a monomorphism and a non-surjective epimorphism, but not an isomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A wide generalization of this example is the localization of a ring by a multiplicative set.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Every localization is a ring epimorphism, which is not, in general, surjective.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] As localizations are fundamental in commutative algebra and algebraic geometry, this may explain why in these areas, the definition of epimorphisms as right cancelable homomorphisms is generally preferred.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] A **split epimorphism** is a homomorphism that has a right inverse and thus it is itself a left inverse of that other homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] That is, a homomorphism $f\colon A\to B$ is a split epimorphism if there exists a homomorphism $g\colon B\to A$ such that $f\circ g=\operatorname {Id} _{B}.$ A split epimorphism is always an epimorphism, for both meanings of *epimorphism*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] For sets and vector spaces, every epimorphism is a split epimorphism, but this property does not hold for most common algebraic structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] the last implication is an equivalence for sets, vector spaces, modules, abelian groups, and groups; the first implication is an equivalence for sets and vector spaces.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Any homomorphism $f:X\to Y$ defines an equivalence relation $\sim$ on X by $a\sim b$ if and only if $f(a)=f(b)$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The relation $\sim$ is called the **kernel** of f .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The quotient set $X/{\sim }$ can then be given a structure of the same type as X , in a natural way, by defining the operations of the quotient set by $[x]\ast [y]=[x\ast y]$ , for each operation $\ast$ of X .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In that case the image of X in Y under the homomorphism f is necessarily isomorphic to $X/\!\sim$ ; this fact is one of the isomorphism theorems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] When the algebraic structure is a group for some operation, the equivalence class K of the identity element of this operation suffices to characterize the equivalence relation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In this case, the quotient by the equivalence relation is denoted by $X/K$ (usually read as " X mod K ").
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Also in this case, it is K , rather than $\sim$ , that is called the kernel of f .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The kernels of homomorphisms of a given type of algebraic structure are naturally equipped with some structure.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In model theory, the notion of an algebraic structure is generalized to structures involving both operations and relations.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Let *L* be a signature consisting of function and relation symbols, and *A*, *B* be two *L*-structures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] In the special case with just one binary relation, we obtain the notion of a graph homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Homomorphisms are also used in the study of formal languages and are often briefly referred to as *morphisms*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] If h is a homomorphism on $\Sigma _{1}^{*}$ and $\varepsilon$ denotes the empty string, then h is called an $\varepsilon$ *-free homomorphism* when $h(x)\neq \varepsilon$ for all $x\neq \varepsilon$ in $\Sigma _{1}^{*}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] If $|h(a)|=1$ for all $a\in \Sigma _{1}$ (that is, h is 1-uniform), then h is also called a *coding* or a *projection*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] The set $\Sigma ^{*}$ of words formed from the alphabet $\Sigma$ may be thought of as the free monoid generated by $\Sigma$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] Here the monoid operation is concatenation and the identity element is the empty word.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/homomorphism] From this perspective, a language homomorphism is precisely a monoid homomorphism.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] In 2024 NIST announced the Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Standard for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] She then showed a cryptographic hash function whose security is equivalent to the computational hardness of SIS.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] In 1998, Jeffrey Hoffstein, Jill Pipher, and Joseph H.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Silverman introduced a lattice-based public-key encryption scheme, known as NTRU.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] However, their scheme is not known to be at least as hard as solving a worst-case lattice problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] The first lattice-based public-key encryption scheme whose security was proven under worst-case hardness assumptions was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005, together with the learning with errors problem (LWE).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Since then, much follow-up work has focused on improving Regev's security proof and improving the efficiency of the original scheme.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Much more work has been devoted to constructing additional cryptographic primitives based on LWE and related problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] For example, in 2009, Craig Gentry introduced the first fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which was based on a lattice problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] In linear algebra, a lattice $L\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the set of all integer linear combinations of vectors from a basis $\{\mathbf {b} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {b} _{n}\}$ of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] In other words, $L={\Big \{}\sum a_{i}\mathbf {b} _{i}:a_{i}\in \mathbb {Z} {\Big \}}.$ For example, $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ is a lattice, generated by the standard basis for $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Crucially, the basis for a lattice is not unique.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] The most important lattice-based computational problem is the shortest vector problem (SVP or sometimes GapSVP), which asks for an approximate minimal Euclidean length of a non-zero lattice vector.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] This problem is thought to be hard to solve efficiently, even with approximation factors that are polynomial in n , and even with a quantum computer.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Many (though not all) lattice-based cryptographic constructions are known to be secure if SVP is in fact hard in this regime.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] This section presents selected lattice-based schemes, grouped by primitive.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] This section lists a selection of lattice-based schemes for the purpose of digital signatures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] CRYSTALS-Dilithium or simply Dilithium is built upon module-LWE and module-SIS.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was selected by the NIST as the basis for a digital signature standard.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] According to a message from Ray Perlner, writing on behalf of the NIST PQC team, the NIST module-LWE signing standard is to be based on version 3.1 of the Dilithium specification.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] NIST's changes on Dilithium 3.1 intend to support additional randomness in signing (hedged signing) and other improvements.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was one of the two digital signature schemes initially chosen by the NIST in their post-quantum cryptography process, the other one being SPHINCS+, which is not based on lattices but on hashes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2023, NIST published FIPS 204 (Initial Public Draft), and started calling Dilithium "Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Algorithm" (ML-DSA).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] As of October 2023, ML-DSA was being implemented as a part of Libgcrypt, according to Falko Strenzke.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2024, NIST officially standardized CRYSTALS-Dilithium under the name ML-DSA, establishing it as the primary standard (FIPS 204) for quantum-resistant digital signatures.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Lattice-based cryptographic constructions hold a great promise for public-key post-quantum cryptography.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Indeed, the main alternative forms of public-key cryptography are schemes based on the hardness of factoring and related problems and schemes based on the hardness of the discrete logarithm and related problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] However, both factoring and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be solvable in polynomial time on a quantum computer.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Furthermore, algorithms for factorization tend to yield algorithms for discrete logarithm, and conversely.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] This further motivates the study of constructions based on alternative assumptions, such as the hardness of lattice problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Many lattice-based cryptographic schemes are known to be secure assuming the *worst-case* hardness of certain lattice problems.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] I.e., if there exists an algorithm that can efficiently break the cryptographic scheme with non-negligible probability, then there exists an efficient algorithm that solves a certain lattice problem on any input.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] However, for the practical lattice-based constructions (such as schemes based on NTRU and even schemes based on LWE with efficient parameters), meaningful reduction-based guarantees of security are not known.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] Some authors who have investigated concrete security for lattice-based cryptosystems have found that the provable security results for such systems do not provide any meaningful concrete security for practical values of the parameters.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] For many cryptographic primitives, the only known constructions are based on lattices or closely related objects.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/lattice-based-cryptography] These primitives include fully homomorphic encryption, indistinguishability obfuscation, cryptographic multilinear maps, and functional encryption.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The **RSA** (**Rivest–Shamir–Adleman**) **cryptosystem** is a family of public-key cryptosystems (one of the oldest), widely used for secure data transmission.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The initialism "RSA" comes from the surnames of Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, who publicly described the algorithm in 1977.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] An equivalent system was developed secretly in 1973 at Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), the British signals intelligence agency, by the English mathematician Clifford Cocks.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] RSA is used in digital signature such as RSASSA-PSS or RSA-FDH, public-key encryption of very short messages (almost always a single-use symmetric key in a hybrid cryptosystem) such as RSAES-OAEP, and public-key key encapsulation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] In RSA-based cryptography, a user's *private key*—which can be used to sign messages, or decrypt messages sent to that user—is a pair of large prime numbers chosen at random and kept secret.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] A user's *public key*—which can be used to verify messages from the user, or encrypt messages so that only that user can decrypt them—is the product of the prime numbers.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The security of RSA is related to the difficulty of factoring the product of two large prime numbers, the "factoring problem".
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Breaking RSA encryption is known as the RSA problem.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Whether it is as difficult as the factoring problem is an open question.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] There are no published methods to defeat the system if a large enough key is used.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The idea of an asymmetric public-private key cryptosystem is attributed to Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman, who published this concept in 1976.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] They also introduced digital signatures and attempted to apply number theory.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Their formulation used a shared-secret-key created from exponentiation of some number, modulo a prime number.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] However, they left open the problem of realizing a one-way function, possibly because the difficulty of factoring was not well-studied at the time.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Moreover, like Diffie-Hellman, RSA is based on modular exponentiation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Leonard Adleman at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology made several attempts over the course of a year to create a function that was hard to invert.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Rivest and Shamir, as computer scientists, proposed many potential functions, while Adleman, as a mathematician, was responsible for finding their weaknesses.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] They tried many approaches, including "knapsack-based" and "permutation polynomials".
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] For a time, they thought what they wanted to achieve was impossible due to contradictory requirements.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] In April 1977, they spent Passover at the house of a student and drank a good deal of wine before returning to their homes at around midnight.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Rivest, unable to sleep, lay on the couch with a math textbook and started thinking about their one-way function.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] He spent the rest of the night formalizing his idea, and he had much of the paper ready by daybreak.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The algorithm is now known as RSA – the initials of their surnames in same order as their paper.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Clifford Cocks, an English mathematician working for the British intelligence agency Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), described a similar system in an internal document in 1973.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] However, given the relatively expensive computers needed to implement it at the time, it was considered to be mostly a curiosity and, as far as is publicly known, was never deployed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] His ideas and concepts were not revealed until 1997 due to its top-secret classification.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Kid-RSA (KRSA) is a simplified, insecure public-key cipher published in 1997, designed for educational purposes.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Kid-RSA gives insight into RSA and other public-key ciphers, analogous to simplified DES.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] A patent describing the RSA algorithm was granted to MIT on 20 September 1983: U.S. patent 4,405,829 "Cryptographic communications system and method".
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] A detailed description of the algorithm was published in August 1977, in *Scientific American*'s Mathematical Games column.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] This preceded the patent's filing date of December 1977.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Consequently, the patent had no legal standing outside the United States.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Had Cocks' work been publicly known, a patent in the United States would not have been legal either.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] When the patent was issued, terms of patent were 17 years.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The patent was about to expire on 21 September 2000, but RSA Security released the algorithm to the public domain on 6 September 2000.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The RSA algorithm involves four steps: key generation, key distribution, public-key operation (used for encryption or verifying a signature), and private key operation (used for decryption or signing a message).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The integers n and e form the public key and d is the private key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The modular exponentiation to the power of e is used in encryption and in verifying signatures, and exponentiation to the power of d is used in decryption and in signing messages.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Compute *λ*(*n*), where λ is Carmichael's totient function.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Determine d as *d* ≡ *e*−1 (mod *λ*(*n*)); that is, d is the modular multiplicative inverse of e modulo *λ*(*n*).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The *public key* consists of the modulus n and the public exponent e.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The *private key* consists of the private exponent d, which must be kept secret. p, q, and *λ*(*n*) must also be kept secret because they can be used to calculate d.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] In fact, they can all be discarded after d has been computed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] In the original RSA paper, the Euler totient function *φ*(*n*) = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1) is used instead of *λ*(*n*) for calculating the private exponent d.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Since *φ*(*n*) is always divisible by *λ*(*n*), the algorithm works as well.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The possibility of using Euler totient function results also from Lagrange's theorem applied to the multiplicative group of integers modulo *pq*.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] However, computing d modulo *φ*(*n*) will sometimes yield a result that is larger than necessary (i.e.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Any "oversized" private exponents not meeting this criterion may always be reduced modulo *λ*(*n*) to obtain a smaller equivalent exponent.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Note: The authors of the original RSA paper carry out the key generation by choosing d and then computing e as the modular multiplicative inverse of d modulo *φ*(*n*), whereas most current implementations of RSA, such as those following PKCS#1, do the reverse—choose e and compute d from it.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Since e can safely be small and fixed, whereas d must be chosen from a large enough space to resist attack, the modern approach can reduce the cost of the public-key operation without loss of security.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Suppose that Bob wants to send secret messages to Alice, or verify messages from Alice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] If they decide to use RSA, Bob must know Alice's public key to encrypt his secret messages or verify Alice's messages, and Alice must use her private key to decrypt Bob's secret messages or sign her own messages.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] To enable Bob to send his encrypted messages or verify her future messages, Alice transmits her public key (*n*, *e*) to Bob via a reliable, but not necessarily secret, route.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Alice's private key (*d*) is never distributed.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] After Bob obtains Alice's public key, he can send a message M to Alice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] To do it, he first turns M into an integer m, the padded plaintext, such that 0 ≤ *m* < *n*, by using an agreed-upon reversible protocol known as a padding scheme.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] This can be done reasonably quickly, even for very large numbers, using modular exponentiation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Note that at least nine values of m will yield a ciphertext c equal to m, but this is very unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Given m, she can recover the original message M by reversing the padding scheme, or discard it as corrupted if the padding is invalid.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Choose any number 1 < *e* < 780 that is coprime to 780.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Choosing a prime number for e leaves us only to check that e is not a divisor of 780.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Both of these calculations can be computed efficiently using the square-and-multiply algorithm for modular exponentiation.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] In real-life situations the primes selected would be much larger; in our example it would be trivial to factor *n* = 3233 (obtained from the freely available public key) back to the primes p and q. e, also from the public key, is then inverted to get d, thus acquiring the private key.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Practical implementations use the Chinese remainder theorem to speed up the calculation using modulus of factors (mod *pq* using mod *p* and mod *q*).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Suppose Alice wishes to send a signed message m to Bob.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] She produces a hash value *h* = hash(*m*) of the message m, raises it to the power of d (modulo n), and attaches *s* = *h**d* mod *n* as a "signature" to the message.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] When Bob receives the message m and signature s, he uses the same hash algorithm in conjunction with Alice's public key to compute *h* = hash(*m*).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The modular exponentiation for signing and verification is the same underlying mathematics as for decryption and encryption, but all the other details of padding scheme for secure public-key encryption and hashing for secure digital signature are different.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The use of a hash, first proposed in 1978 by Michael O.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] The proof of the correctness of RSA is based on Fermat's little theorem, stating that *a**p* − 1 ≡ 1 (mod *p*) for any integer a and prime p, not dividing a.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] We want to show that $(m^{e})^{d}\equiv m{\pmod {pq}}$ for every integer m when p and q are distinct prime numbers and e and d are positive integers satisfying *ed* ≡ 1 (mod *λ*(*pq*)).
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] Since *λ*(*pq*) = lcm(*p* − 1, *q* − 1) is, by construction, divisible by both *p* − 1 and *q* − 1, we can write $ed-1=h(p-1)=k(q-1)$ for some nonnegative integers h and k.
[src:homomorphic-encryption/rsa-cryptosystem] To check whether two numbers, such as m*ed* and m, are congruent mod *pq*, it suffices (and in fact is equivalent) to check that they are congruent mod *p* and mod *q* separately.
